      <hedline>
        <hl1>To Recruit More Police</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from former New York City Police Commissioner Patrick V Murphy comments on October 16 letter on police-hiring crisis</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>An Oct. 16 letter writer believes that a leadership institute being formed by the New York State Association of Chiefs of Police and the State University of New York will help solve the police-hiring crisis. That seems unlikely. Small towns are overrepresented in the group, and cities, especially New York, are underrepresented.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>An Oct. 16 letter writer believes that a leadership institute being formed by the New York State Association of Chiefs of Police and the State University of New York will help solve the police-hiring crisis. That seems unlikely. Small towns are overrepresented in the group, and cities, especially New York, are underrepresented.</p>
        <p>The solution to the police-hiring crisis is to consolidate hundreds of departments that are too small and waste millions of tax dollars. State government should require this and financially assist New York and other principal cities to level the playing field with Nassau and Suffolk Counties. They pay officers $20,000 more than New York's Finest.</p>
        <p>PATRICK V. MURPHY  Bethesda, Md., Oct. 19, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer, executive director of the American Police Association, was New York City's police commissioner, 1970-73.</p>
      </block>
